Defining some visualization functions to plot accuracy, loss and confusion matrix:¶

In [3]:
def plot_metric(hist, metric="accuracy"):
    plt.figure()
    plt.ioff()
    plt.plot(hist.history[metric])
    plt.plot(hist.history[("val_" + metric)])
    plt.title(("model " + metric))
    plt.ylabel(metric)
    plt.xlabel("epoch")
    plt.legend(["train", "validation"], loc="upper left")
    
def plot_loss(hist):
    plt.figure()
    plt.ioff()
    plt.plot(hist.history["loss"])
    plt.plot(hist.history["val_loss"])
    plt.title("model loss")
    plt.ylabel("loss")
    plt.xlabel("epoch")
    plt.legend(["train", "validation"], loc="upper left")
    


def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes, normalize=False, cmap=plt.cm.Blues, tight=False, silent=True):

    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation="nearest", cmap=cmap)
    
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=90)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)
    
    if normalize:
        cm = cm.astype("float") / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        plt.title("Normalized Confusion Matrix")
    else:
        plt.title("Confusion Matrix")

    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, cm[i, j],
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")
    if tight:
        plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylim(len(cm)-0.5, -0.5)
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")
    
    if silent:
        return
    else:
        return cm

Extract numpy arrays from dataframe:¶

In [5]:
X_mfcc40 = train_df.loc[0, ["MFCC_40"]][0]
X_mfcc60 = train_df.loc[0, ["MFCC_60"]][0]
X_mfcc80 = train_df.loc[0, ["MFCC_80"]][0]
X_chroma = train_df.loc[0, ["Chromagram"]][0]
X_melspec = train_df.loc[0, ["Melspectrogram"]][0]
X_all = np.concatenate([X_mfcc80, X_chroma, X_melspec, train_df.loc[0, ["Contrast"]][0], train_df.loc[0, ["Tonnetz"]][0]])

y = np.array([train_df.loc[0, ["ClassID"]]])

for index, row in train_df.iterrows():
    if index == 0:
        continue
    X_mfcc40 = np.vstack([X_mfcc40, row["MFCC_40"]])
    X_mfcc60 = np.vstack([X_mfcc60, row["MFCC_60"]])
    X_mfcc80 = np.vstack([X_mfcc80, row["MFCC_80"]])
    X_chroma = np.vstack([X_chroma, row["Chromagram"]])
    X_melspec = np.vstack([X_melspec, row["Melspectrogram"]])
    tmp = np.concatenate([row["MFCC_80"], row["Chromagram"], row["Melspectrogram"], row["Contrast"], row["Tonnetz"]])
    X_all = np.vstack([X_all, tmp])
    y = np.vstack([y, np.array([row["ClassID"]])])

Defining MLP architectures:¶

In [9]:
# MLP with 2 ReLU layers
def get_MLP1(input_dim, classes):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(512, input_dim=input_dim, activation="relu"))
    model.add(Dense(512, activation="relu"))
    model.add(Dense(classes))
    model.add(Activation("softmax"))
    
    return model

# MLP with 3 ReLU layers
def get_MLP2(input_dim, classes):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(512, input_dim=input_dim, activation="relu"))
    model.add(Dense(512, activation="relu"))
    model.add(Dense(512, activation="relu"))
    model.add(Dense(classes))
    model.add(Activation("softmax"))
    
    return model

# MLP with 2 ReLU layers + batchnorm, kernel- & bias regularization, dropout
def get_MLP3(input_dim, classes):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dense(512, input_dim=input_dim, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01), bias_regularizer=l2(0.01)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    model.add(Dense(512, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01), bias_regularizer=l2(0.01)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    model.add(Dense(classes))
    model.add(Activation("softmax"))
    
    return model

# MLP with 3 ReLU layers + batchnorm, kernel- & bias regularization, dropout
def get_MLP4(input_dim, classes):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dense(512, input_dim=input_dim, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01), bias_regularizer=l2(0.01)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    model.add(Dense(512, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01), bias_regularizer=l2(0.01)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    model.add(Dense(512, activation="relu", kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01), bias_regularizer=l2(0.01)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    model.add(Dense(classes))
    model.add(Activation("softmax"))
    
    return model

# MLP with 2 SELU layers
def get_MLP5(input_dim, classes):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(512, input_dim=input_dim, kernel_initializer="lecun_normal", activation="selu"))
    model.add(Dense(512, kernel_initializer="lecun_normal", activation="selu"))
    model.add(Dense(classes))
    model.add(Activation("softmax"))
    
    return model

# MLP with 2 SELU layers + batchnorm, kernel- & bias regularization, dropout
def get_MLP6(input_dim, classes):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dense(512, input_dim=input_dim, kernel_initializer="lecun_normal", activation="selu", kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01), bias_regularizer=l2(0.01)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    model.add(Dense(512, kernel_initializer="lecun_normal", activation="selu", kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01), bias_regularizer=l2(0.01)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    model.add(Dense(classes))
    model.add(Activation("softmax"))
    
    return model

MLP Architecture 1 - MFCC80¶

In [28]:
# get features, train & validation split
X_train, X_val, y_train_og, y_val_og = train_test_split(X_mfcc80, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=1337, stratify=y)

# encode response
y_train = to_categorical(y_train_og)
y_val = to_categorical(y_val_og)

# reshape response
y_train_flat = np.reshape(y_train_og, (y_train_og.shape[0],)).astype("int64")
y_val_flat = np.reshape(y_val_og, (y_val_og.shape[0],)).astype("int64")

# define model
model = get_MLP1(X_train.shape[1], 10)

opt = optimizers.SGD(lr=0.001, momentum=0.9)
model.compile(optimizer=opt , loss="categorical_crossentropy", metrics=["accuracy"])

model_name = "mlp_1_mfcc80"

callbacks=[]
callbacks.append(EarlyStopping(monitor="val_loss", patience=15, verbose=0, mode="auto"))
callbacks.append(ModelCheckpoint(model_name+"_check_.h5", save_best_only=True, monitor="val_loss", mode="min"))

# train model
hist = model.fit(X_train, y_train, batch_size=128, epochs=1000, validation_data=(X_val, y_val), callbacks=callbacks, verbose=0)

# plot training history
plot_metric(hist)

plot_loss(hist)

# get model quality
predictions_train = np.argmax(model.predict(X_train), axis=1)
predictions_val = np.argmax(model.predict(X_val), axis=1)

val_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_val_flat, predictions_val)
print("Train Accuracy: ", accuracy_score(y_train_flat, predictions_train))
print("Validation Accuracy: ", val_accuracy)
models.append(model_name)
val_accuracies.append(val_accuracy)

# plot training cm
conf = confusion_matrix(y_train_flat, predictions_train)

plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
plot = plot_confusion_matrix(conf, classes=classes)
plt.show()

# plot validation cm
conf = confusion_matrix(y_val_flat, predictions_val)

plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
plot = plot_confusion_matrix(conf, classes=classes)
plt.show()

# save model
model.save((model_name + ".h5"))

Validation Accuracy:  0.8928571428571429
